        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "On-Call Sustainability as an Engineering System Property"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "On-call fatigue is an engineering system property, not a personal one. When engineers receive more than 8 off-hours pages per week, sleep quality degrades, cognitive performance drops, and response quality during incidents declines \u2014 this is well-documented in occupational health research. More practically, engineers leave teams where on-call is routinely painful, and the institutional knowledge they take with them is harder to replace than the operational toil that drove them out."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Designing on-call compensation and fatigue management is therefore a reliability concern, not just a people management one. A rotation with chronic high toil will eventually produce slower incident response, missed pages, and turnover \u2014 all of which directly degrade the reliability of the GenAI system the on-call program is meant to protect."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "On-call fatigue zones by weekly off-hours interruption count, compensation framework components, and toil reduction playbook"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Defining Sustainable On-Call"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Google's SRE book defines a sustainable on-call as one where on-call work consumes no more than 25% of an engineer's work time. A simpler operational proxy is the off-hours interruption count: the number of times an engineer is paged outside business hours (typically 22:00\u201308:00 local time) during a one-week shift. Four or fewer off-hours interruptions per week is the sustainable target; eight or more requires intervention."
          }
        ]
      },
