      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Measure off-hours interruption count per engineer per shift, not per team. Team-level averages hide situations where one engineer in a rotation consistently receives more pages than others due to schedule coverage gaps or timezone placement."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Three Compensation Components"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "On-call compensation has three distinct components that address different aspects of the burden. Confusing them leads to a compensation structure that incentivizes the wrong behaviors."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "1. On-Call Stipend"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A fixed weekly payment for being on the rotation, independent of how many pages the engineer actually receives. This compensates for the availability constraint itself \u2014 the engineer cannot drink alcohol, must keep their phone charged and audible, and must be able to respond within 15 minutes regardless of what they are doing. The stipend is paid for every shift week whether quiet or busy."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "2. Incident Pay"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A per-incident payment for P1 and P2 pages received outside business hours. This compensates for the actual interruption. Unlike the stipend, it scales with load \u2014 a busy week produces more incident pay. This creates a measurement incentive: teams that reduce alert noise lower on-call costs, and that cost reduction is visible to managers."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Do not pay per alert acknowledgement \u2014 that creates an incentive to silence alerts without resolving them. Pay per incident (a group of alerts representing one operational event), which is the unit the on-call engineer actually works on."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "3. Compensatory Time"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Recovery days granted after high-toil shifts. The rule is simple: one compensatory day for every five off-hours pages above zero during the shift week. These must be taken within two weeks of the shift \u2014 not carried indefinitely \u2014 to serve their recovery purpose. Compensatory time is the most effective tool for preventing cumulative fatigue from building up over multiple rotation cycles."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Toil Measurement Implementation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# toil_tracker.py \u2014 weekly on-call toil report from PagerDuty data\nimport os\nimport requests\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\n\nPD_API_KEY = os.environ['PAGERDUTY_API_KEY']\nSLACK_WEBHOOK = os.environ['SLACK_ONCALL_WEBHOOK']\n\nHEADERS = {\n    'Authorization': f'Token token={PD_API_KEY}',\n    'Accept': 'application/vnd.pagerduty+json;version=2',\n}\n\nOFF_HOURS_START = 22  # 22:00 local\nOFF_HOURS_END   = 8   # 08:00 local\n\n@dataclass\nclass WeeklyToilReport:\n    engineer: str\n    week_start: datetime\n    total_pages: int\n    off_hours_pages: int\n    p1_pages: int\n    p2_pages: int\n\n    @property\n    def fatigue_zone(self) -> str:\n        n = self.off_hours_pages\n        if n <= 4:\n            return 'sustainable'\n        elif n <= 8:\n            return 'elevated'\n        elif n <= 15:\n            return 'high_toil'\n        return 'unsustainable'\n\n    @property\n    def comp_days_owed(self) -> int:\n        if self.off_hours_pages >= 5:\n            return self.off_hours_pages // 5\n        return 0\n\ndef is_off_hours(dt: datetime) -> bool:\n    hour = dt.hour\n    return hour >= OFF_HOURS_START or hour < OFF_HOURS_END\n\ndef fetch_incidents_for_user(\n    user_id: str,\n    since: datetime,\n    until: datetime,\n) -> list[dict]:\n    resp = requests.get(\n        'https://api.pagerduty.com/incidents',\n        headers=HEADERS,\n        params={\n            'user_ids[]': user_id,\n            'since': since.isoformat(),\n            'until': until.isoformat(),\n            'statuses[]': ['triggered', 'acknowledged', 'resolved'],\n            'limit': 100,\n        },\n        timeout=10,\n    )\n    return resp.json().get('incidents', [])\n\ndef build_weekly_report(\n    user_name: str,\n    user_id: str,\n    week_start: datetime,\n) -> WeeklyToilReport:\n    week_end = week_start + timedelta(days=7)\n    incidents = fetch_incidents_for_user(user_id, week_start, week_end)\n\n    off_hours = 0\n    p1 = 0\n    p2 = 0\n    for inc in incidents:\n        created = datetime.fromisoformat(\n            inc['created_at'].replace('Z', '+00:00')\n        )\n        if is_off_hours(created):\n            off_hours += 1\n        urgency = inc.get('urgency', '')\n        if urgency == 'high':\n            p1 += 1\n        elif urgency == 'low':\n            p2 += 1\n\n    return WeeklyToilReport(\n        engineer=user_name,\n        week_start=week_start,\n        total_pages=len(incidents),\n        off_hours_pages=off_hours,\n        p1_pages=p1,\n        p2_pages=p2,\n    )\n\ndef post_toil_report(report: WeeklyToilReport) -> None:\n    zone_emoji = {\n        'sustainable':   ':white_check_mark:',\n        'elevated':      ':warning:',\n        'high_toil':     ':no_entry:',\n        'unsustainable': ':rotating_light:',\n    }\n    emoji = zone_emoji[report.fatigue_zone]\n    lines = [\n        f'*On-Call Toil Report \u2014 week of {report.week_start.strftime(\"%Y-%m-%d\")}*',\n        f'Engineer: {report.engineer}',\n        f'{emoji} Fatigue zone: {report.fatigue_zone}',\n        f'Total pages: {report.total_pages} | '\n        f'Off-hours: {report.off_hours_pages} | '\n        f'P1: {report.p1_pages} | P2: {report.p2_pages}',\n    ]\n    if report.comp_days_owed:\n        lines.append(\n            f':calendar: Comp days owed: {report.comp_days_owed} '\n            '(take within 2 weeks)'\n        )\n    if report.fatigue_zone == 'unsustainable':\n        lines.append(\n            ':rotating_light: ACTION REQUIRED: '\n            'Escalate to EM today. Add backup on-call.'\n        )\n    requests.post(\n        SLACK_WEBHOOK,\n        json={'text': '\\n'.join(lines)},\n        timeout=5,\n    )\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Run this report automatically every Monday after the handoff. Post to the team's Slack channel and CC the EM. The fatigue zone and comp_days_owed fields provide the EM with everything needed to take action without requiring the engineer to self-report their workload."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Alert Audit: The Primary Toil Reduction Tool"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The most effective way to reduce on-call toil is to eliminate alerts that fire without producing action. An alert that wakes an engineer at 2:00 AM and then resolves on its own without any remediation is not useful \u2014 it is operational noise that costs sleep and attention. Audit alert action rates regularly and aggressively prune low-action-rate alerts."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# alert_audit.py \u2014 identifies noisy alerts that should be tuned or deleted\nfrom collections import defaultdict\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\n\n@dataclass\nclass AlertFireRecord:\n    alert_name: str\n    fired_at: str\n    acknowledged_at: str | None\n    resolved_at: str | None\n    action_taken: bool  # did the on-call engineer take any action?\n\ndef audit_alert_noise(\n    records: list[AlertFireRecord],\n    lookback_weeks: int = 4,\n) -> dict[str, dict]:\n    \"\"\"\n    For each alert, compute:\n    - fire_count: how many times it fired\n    - action_rate: fraction of fires where action was taken\n    - recommendation: tune / delete / keep\n\n    Alerts with action_rate < 0.3 over 4 weeks are candidates for deletion.\n    Alerts with action_rate < 0.6 are candidates for threshold tuning.\n    \"\"\"\n    by_alert: dict[str, list[AlertFireRecord]] = defaultdict(list)\n    for r in records:\n        by_alert[r.alert_name].append(r)\n\n    results = {}\n    for name, fires in by_alert.items():\n        total = len(fires)\n        actions = sum(1 for f in fires if f.action_taken)\n        action_rate = actions / total if total > 0 else 0.0\n\n        if action_rate < 0.3:\n            recommendation = 'DELETE \u2014 no action taken in 70%+ of fires'\n        elif action_rate < 0.6:\n            recommendation = 'TUNE \u2014 threshold too sensitive or window too short'\n        else:\n            recommendation = 'KEEP'\n\n        results[name] = {\n            'fire_count': total,\n            'action_rate': round(action_rate, 2),\n            'recommendation': recommendation,\n        }\n\n    return dict(sorted(results.items(), key=lambda x: x[1]['action_rate']))\n\n# Example usage\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    import json\n    # records would come from PagerDuty incident log with action_taken\n    # annotated by the on-call engineer in the incident notes\n    sample = [\n        AlertFireRecord('EvalQualityBurnHigh', '2026-06-01', '2026-06-01', '2026-06-01', True),\n        AlertFireRecord('EvalQualityBurnHigh', '2026-06-05', '2026-06-05', '2026-06-05', False),\n        AlertFireRecord('ProviderLatencySpike', '2026-06-02', None, '2026-06-02', False),\n        AlertFireRecord('ProviderLatencySpike', '2026-06-08', None, '2026-06-08', False),\n        AlertFireRecord('ProviderLatencySpike', '2026-06-14', None, '2026-06-14', False),\n    ]\n    results = audit_alert_noise(sample)\n    print(json.dumps(results, indent=2))\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The action_taken field requires the on-call engineer to annotate each PagerDuty incident with whether they took action. This takes 30 seconds per incident and produces the data needed for the audit. Build this annotation into the incident resolution workflow \u2014 make it part of the PD incident form or the Jira ticket close checklist."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Toil Reduction Playbook"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When the weekly toil report shows an elevated or high-toil zone, run through these interventions in order. Do not skip to rotation size increase without first attempting alert tuning \u2014 adding engineers to a rotation does not fix noisy alerts, it just distributes the noise."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Alert audit: for every alert that fired without action in the past 4 weeks, either raise the threshold, add a dual-window requirement, or delete the alert"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Runbook automation: if the runbook action for an alert is always the same command, automate it \u2014 the remediation runs automatically and the engineer is not paged"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Business-hours reclassification: non-urgent alerts (eval quality trend, budget drift warnings) should page only during business hours; the on-call engineer is notified at the start of their workday instead of overnight"
                  }
                ]
              }
